# Operating Systems & Command-Line Fundamentals

This folder contains applied coursework demonstrating practical use of operating system concepts across **Windows and Linux** environments, with a focus on command-line interaction and basic automation.

The work links operating system theory with hands-on usage of CLI tools to manage files, directories, and system resources.

## What This Project Covers

- Core operating system concepts (Windows & Linux)
- File system management (create, move, rename, copy, delete)
- Command-line navigation and syntax
- Use of Windows Command Prompt and Linux Terminal
- Introduction to automation using scripts

## Practical Skills Demonstrated

- Confident use of CLI commands in both Windows and Linux
- File and directory management using terminal tools
- Understanding of how operating systems manage resources
- Verification of actions through command output
- Clear documentation of technical steps and outcomes

## Automation & Scripting (Foundational)

- **Windows Batch scripting** used to automate simple, repeatable tasks
- Commands executed sequentially to create, move, display, and delete files
- Conditional logic (`if / else`) used to verify successful execution
- Comparison between Batch scripting (Windows) and Bash concepts (Linux)

> Note: This project focuses on **foundational scripting concepts**, not advanced automation or production scripts.

## Tools & Technologies

- Windows Command Prompt
- Linux Terminal (CLI)
- Windows Batch files
- Standard OS utilities (mkdir, move/mv, copy/cp, dir/ls, del/rm, echo, cat)

## Why This Matters

This project demonstrates how operating systems enable:
- Efficient file management
- Direct system interaction via CLI
- Basic automation to reduce manual effort
- Reliable execution of repeatable tasks

All examples use **simulated data and environments** and are designed to reflect real-world administrative scenarios.

---

*This work forms part of an Applied Computing degree and focuses on accuracy, clarity, and practical understanding rather than advanced scripting complexity.*
